[vscode.d.ts#L3540](/Microsoft/vscode/blob/1.11.2/src/vs/vscode.d.ts#L3540)
```typescript
export function registerCommand(command: string, callback: (...args: any[]) => any, thisArg?: any): Disposable;
```

[extHost.api.impl.ts#L152-L154](/Microsoft/vscode/blob/1.11.2/src/vs/workbench/api/node/extHost.api.impl.ts#L152-L154)
```typescript
registerCommand<T>(id: string, command: <T>(...args: any[]) => T | Thenable<T>, thisArgs?: any): vscode.Disposable {
	return extHostCommands.registerCommand(id, command, thisArgs);
}
```

[extHostCommands.ts#L54](/Microsoft/vscode/blob/1.11.2/src/vs/workbench/api/node/extHostCommands.ts#L54)
```typescript
registerCommand(id: string, callback: <T>(...args: any[]) => T | Thenable<T>, thisArg?: any, description?: ICommandHandlerDescription): extHostTypes.Disposable {
//...
}
```

Wouldn't it makes sense to expose the ICommandHandlerDescription to the extensions that register commands? I would want some of my commands to accept parameters as an URI, the same way we can do it with `vscode.previewHtml`
```typescript
let href = encodeURI('command:vscode.previewHtml?' + JSON.stringify(someUri));
let html = '<a href="' + href + '">Show Resource...</a>.';
```
This would make it easier to display HTML pages to the user, with clickable links that would trigger commands with parameters

@jrieken this is similar to what you've done previously in b5525f9ac3c8f079e4171525a39cb6bb52177c57 so any chance we can bring it back?
